In article <phrCuILo0.JFE@netcom.com> phr@netcom.com (Paul Rubin) writes:
>From: phr@netcom.com (Paul Rubin)
>Subject: Re: Man-in-the-middle vs Clipper, thanks FBI?
>Date: Sun, 14 Aug 1994 07:47:59 GMT

>In article <32jan5$1s7@apakabar.cc.columbia.edu>,
>Josh P Hendrix <jph19@namaste.cc.columbia.edu> wrote:
>>Does anyone know enough about the technical specifics of the FBI
>>Wiretap sections of the Digital Telephony bill to tell me whether or
>>not they would allow someone to perform a man-in-the-middle attack
>>against a Clipper- encoded conversation? Specifically, would an agent
>>be able to add a device to the phone switch that would enable him/her
>>to route both ends of a conversation through a 'black box' without
>>the detection?

>That is pretty much the definition of a wiretap, but "man-in-the-middle"
>usually refers to faking out a key exchange protocol, which is
>a bit different.

If said agent is using two Clippers, he _is_ faking out a key exchange 
protocol:

Your clipper talks to his input clipper.  He listens to it's output while 
feeding it into his output clipper.  Your intended recipient receives that.
Distortion, insertion of false data, playback of previously recorded voice, et 
al, optional.

Dave Merriman

